# Public Prosecutor _v_ Muhammad Fiqkri Jaffri  

### \[2022\] SGDC 223

<table id="info-table"><tbody><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Case Number</td><td class="txt-body">District Arrest Case No 904101 of 2020 &amp; Ors, Magistrate's Appeal No. 9098-2022-01</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Decision Date</td><td class="txt-body">22 September 2022</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Tribunal/Court</td><td class="txt-body">District Court</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Coram</td><td class="txt-body">Brenda Tan</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Counsel Name(s)</td><td class="txt-body">Deputy Public Prosecutor Dwayne Lum (Attorney General's Chambers) for the Public Prosecutor; Koo Man Ling Audrey (Populus Law Corporation) for the accused.</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Parties</td><td class="txt-body">Public Prosecutor — Muhammad Fiqkri Jaffri</td></tr></tbody></table>

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9098/2022/01.\]

22 September 2022

### District Judge Brenda Tan:

## Introduction

1       On 23 February 2020, at about 4.08am at a HDB void deck, the accused, Muhammad Fiqkri Jaffri, a 28-year-old male Singaporean, together with his twin brother, Muhammad Farhan Jaffri (“Farhan”), punched and kicked a police officer multiple times on his face and body resulting in the police officer being unable to follow his ordinary pursuits for 29 days. A few minutes later, around 4.15am, at the service road near the void deck, the accused headbutted a different police officer on the nose causing that police officer to suffer a nasal fracture and laceration and be given five days of outpatient sick leave. The Prosecution described this case as one of the worse instances of brutal, senseless, and gratuitous violence inflicted on police officers to date[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1).

2       The accused was legally represented. He faced a total of seven charges. He pleaded guilty to five proceeded charges and consented to have the remaining two charges taken into consideration (“TIC”) for the purpose of sentencing. I sentenced him to a total of 54 months’ imprisonment (four and a half years’ imprisonment) and six strokes of the cane. The individual sentences that I imposed are set out in the table at \[12\] and \[42\] below.

3       The accused, being dissatisfied with his sentence subsequently filed this appeal from prison where he is presently serving his jail term.

## The five proceeded charges

4       The five charges which the accused pleaded guilty to comprised three counts under the Penal Code, Cap 224 (“PC”), one count under the Vandalism Act, Cap 341 (“VA”) and one count under the Societies Act, Cap 311 (“SA”). The PC charges and the VA charge were committed on the same day on 23 February 2020 in the vicinity of Blk 755 Jurong West Street 74 (“Block 755”). The first PC offence was under s 333 read with (“r/w”) s 34 for causing grievous hurt to Sergeant Chong Jia Wei who was discharging his duty as a public servant at about 4.08am at the void deck of Block 755, in furtherance of the common intention with Farhan. I shall refer to this charge as the “**common intention to cause grievous hurt charge**”. The second PC offence was under s 333 for causing grievous hurt to Sergeant Chen Jian Da who was also discharging his duty as a public servant at about 4.15am at the service road at Block 755. I shall refer to this charge as the “**grievous hurt charge**”. The third PC offence was under s 506 (second limb) for committing criminal intimidation against Sergeant Irfan at about 4.15am at the service road at Block 755 by threatening him with death by uttering words in Malay which meant “I let go of this thing, I shoot you until die”. I shall refer to this charge as the “**criminal intimidation charge”**. The VA charge was under s 3 for an offence of vandalism by kicking the rear right passenger door of a Police Fast Response Car at about 4.40am at the service road at Block 755 while the accused was seated at the rear passenger seat, causing the door to be misaligned which cost $1,255.48 to repair. I shall refer to this charge as the “**vandalism charge**”. The SA charge was under s 14(3) for being a member of an unlawful society called “Sio Kun Tong” between 22 March 2018 and 26 June 2020[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2). I shall refer to this charge as the “**member of unlawful society charge**”.

5       The five proceeded charges are set out in Annex A.

## The two TIC charges

6       The two TIC charges were for offences under s 6 of the Protection from Harassment Act, Cap 256A for using abusive words against two different police officers on 23 February 2020 at about 4.15am and 4.30am respectively at or around Block 755.

7       The TIC charges are set out in Annex B.

## The statement of facts

8       The accused admitted without qualification to the statement of facts (“SOF”) which formed the basis of his conviction. The SOF is reproduced below except for the attachments which consisted of supporting documents such as the medical reports of the injured police officers and photographs of their injuries.

> 1.    The accused is Muhammad Fiqkri Jaffri (“Fiqkri”), a 28-year-old Singaporean male bearing NRIC No: XXX. He was an odd-job worker at the material time of the offence.

> 2.    The co-accused is Muhammad Farhan Jaffri (“Farhan”), a 28-year-old Singaporean male bearing NRIC No: XXX. He is the accused’s twin brother and has since been dealt with for his involvement in this offence.

> 3.    The parties involved are:

>> a.    Sergeant Chong Jia Wei (“Sgt Chong”), a 27-year-old Singaporean male.

>> b.    Staff Sergeant Tity Sumarni Bte Abd Ghani (“SSgt Sumarni”), a 35-year-old Singaporean female.

>> c.    Sergeant Muhammad Irfan Bin Misran (“Sgt Irfan”), a 22-year-old Singaporean male.

>> d.    Sergeant Charmaine Tan (“Sgt Charmaine”), a 27-year-old Singaporean female.

> 4.    The four involved parties are all police officers attached to Nanyang Neighbourhood Police Centre as a Ground Response Officers. At the time of the offence, the victims were in their police uniform and conducting patrol duties. The four police officers will be referred to collectively as the “Police Officers”.

> **FIRST INFORMATION REPORT**

> 5.    On 23 February 2020 at around 4.00 am, Farhan was having an argument with his wife at the void deck of Block 755 Jurong West Street 74, Singapore. As there was a commotion, a member of the public called the police and the Police Officers were dispatched to the incident location to conduct checks.

> **Facts relating to first charge DAC-904101-2020 (section 333 r/w section 34 Penal Code)**

> 6.    Investigations revealed that the accused and Farhan had been sharing a bottle of “Smirnoff” whisky together at their home located at #XXX of Blk 755 Jurong West Street 74 at around 1.30am on 23 February 2020. At about 3am, whilst the accused and Farhan were drinking, Farhan’s wife arrived at their home and quarreled with Farhan. The accused did not notice what they were quarrelling about. As the accused’s parents were already sleeping, the accused told Farhan and his wife to go to the void deck to continue quarrelling so as not to wake their parents up. Farhan and his wife then went to the void deck to continue their argument.

> 7.    When the Police Officers arrived at the incident location at around 4.03 am in response to the call from the member of the public, they saw Farhan and his wife and observed that his wife was crying. SSgt Sumarni went forward to speak to Farhan, asking them if they were alright. Instead of answering SSgt Sumarni’s queries, Farhan started hurling vulgarities at SSgt Sumarni. The accused heard Farhan’s shouts from the void deck and left his home to go downstairs via the staircase.

> 8.    As the Police Officers were engaging Farhan, the accused came down to the void deck from a nearby staircase. He immediately approached the Police Officers aggressively and pointed his finger in the Police Officers’ faces while demanding to know what was wrong as they were speaking with Farhan. At the same time, the accused told Farhan and his wife to go back to his unit located on the second floor, while gesturing aggressively at the Police Officers and telling them to “zip” their mouth and “shut up”. After some time, Farhan relented and left the void deck, but continued to hurl abusive language at SSgt Sumarni as he went up the staircase.

> 9.    After Farhan left, the accused aggressively pointed his index finger towards the Police Officers faces and asked them police officers “what’s wrong?” repeatedly. SSgt Sumarni told the accused to calm down and stated that she was just trying to ask Farhan what had happened between his wife and him. The accused told SSgt Sumarni that this was a matter between Farhan and his wife and demanded for the Police Officers to not interfere.

> 10.    During this entire time, the Police Officers told the accused to “relax” and kept explaining that they were simply concerned about Farhan’s wife, who was teary eyed. However, the accused not only refused to calm down, he got increasingly agitated at the Police Officers. Sgt Chong informed the accused that they just wanted to know what happened earlier between Farhan and his wife. Sgt Irfan also informed the accused that they were not there for the accused. SSgt Sumarni also explained to the accused that they saw Farhan’s wife crying and simply wanted to know what was happening. Instead of calming down, the accused continued to act aggressively towards the police officers, pointing at their faces and repeatedly telling them that it was a relationship issue between Farhan and his wife, that there was “nothing” and that the accused would “handle” the situation. Both SSgt Sumarni and Sgt Irfan told him “ok”. The accused continued however to approach Sgt Irfan aggressively, asking him again if he was ok with the accused’s suggestion. Sgt Irfan backed away from the accused in an attempt to de-escalate the situation and told the accused “can, no problem”.

> 11.    At this point, Farhan returned and shouted at the Police Officers, hurling vulgarities at SSgt Sumarni. SSgt Sumarni tried speaking with Farhan to explain that she was just asking Farhan why his wife was crying earlier. Farhan however continued shouting vulgarities at SSgt Sumarni.

> 12.    The accused then grabbed Farhan on the back of his neck and attempted to get Farhan’s attention, as Farhan was still shouting at the Police Officers. Farhan told the accused he did not like Sgt Chong’s face. The accused then asked Farhan repeatedly if he wanted the accused to “shoot” Sgt Chong, whilst holding up a fist. The accused meant that he wanted Farhan to tell him if he wanted the accused to punch Sgt Chong.

> 13.    Suddenly, at around 4.08 am, the accused turned to Sgt Chong, who was standing behind him, and punched Sgt Chong, a public servant in the discharge of his duty, once in the face with his right fist with the intention to cause grievous hurt. The punch caused Sgt Chong to fall to the ground and his spectacles to fall off. Having developed a common intention to cause grievous hurt to Sgt Chong, Farhan immediately joined in and the accused and Farhan started punching and kicking SGT Chong multiple times on the face and body. SGT Chong recovered briefly and pinned the accused to the ground, who was still punching him multiple times on his face and body.

> 14.    Meanwhile, Sgt Irfan and Sgt Charmaine restrained Farhan. However, Farhan refused to cooperate. He then spat at Sgt Irfan’s face and hurled vulgarities at him. Farhan also punched Sgt Irfan’s face multiple times and kicked him in the stomach.

> 15.    At around 4.10 am, Farhan broke loose from Sgt Irfan and Sgt Charmaine’s restrains and kicked Sgt Chong in the head while Sgt Chong was restraining the accused. The kick was so forceful that it caused Sgt Chong to bleed from his left ear and to release his grip on the accused, who promptly started punching and kicking Sgt Chong on his face and body.

> 16.    SSgt Sumarni then drew her baton and told the accused to cooperate. As the accused did not stop assaulting Sgt Chong, SSgt Sumarni hit him with her baton. However, not only did the accused refuse to cooperate, he taunted SSgt Sumarni by pointing to himself and said that he was from “Sio Kun Tong”, a secret society. He also uttered the words “shoot, shoot, shoot!”, which was a reference to beating someone up, and proceeded to punch Sgt Chong again in the head. Sgt Chong was at this time attempting to restrain Farhan on the ground in front of Fiqkri. Fiqkri saw that Sgt Chong was occupied with restraining Farhan and punched Sgt Chong repeatedly in the head and body. This was despite SSgt Sumarni attempting to restrain him with her baton.

> 17.    The accused’s assault on Sgt Chong only stopped when his family members came to the void deck and helped the Police Officers restrain Farhan and move him away. This led to Sgt Chong being able to also move away from Fiqkri. The entire assault on Sgt Chong by Farhan and Fiqkri on Sgt Chong lasted for at least two and a half minutes and was captured on SSgt Sumarni’s body-worn camera footage. Sgt Chong was at this point already bleeding from the ear and head as a result of the assault.

> 18.    Sgt Chong was subsequently conveyed by ambulance to Ng Teng Fong General Hospital. As a result of the assault by the accused and Farhan, Sgt Chong sustained the following injuries:

>> a.    Concussion injury of the head;

>> b.    Contusions on the left side of his face;

>> c.    Laceration over left ear; and

>> d.    Abrasions over left lower eye lid.

> 19.    He was admitted for two days in the neurosurgery ward for further monitoring. He was diagnosed as having a traumatic head injury and was given 29 days hospitalization leave, during the space of which he was unable to follow his ordinary pursuits.

> 20.    By virtue of the foregoing, the accused has, together with Farhan and in furtherance of the common intention of them both, thereby voluntarily caused grievous hurt to the victim, who is a public servant in the discharge of his duty as such public servant, and he has thereby committed an offence punishable under section 333 read with section 34 of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed) (“Penal Code”).

> 21.    As a result of her attempts to restrain the accused as he was punching and kicking Sgt Chong, SSgt Sumarni sustained swelling to both her forearms and pain to her right shoulder. She however did not seek medical treatment for her injuries.

> **Facts relating to fifth charge DAC-919124-2020 (section 506 Penal Code)**

> 22.    Shortly after, additional police officers arrived at the scene:

>> a.    Sergeant Lee Tze Ting (“Sgt Lee”), a 27-year-old Singaporean female.

>> b.    Sergeant Chen Jian Da (“Sgt Chen”), a 28-year-old Singaporean male.

> Sgt Lee and Sgt Chen are police officers attached to Nanyang Neighbourhood Police Centre as a Ground Response Officers. At the time of the offence, the victims were in their police uniform and conducting patrol duties.

> 23.    Following their assault on Sgt Chong, SSgt Sumarni and Sgt Irfan attempted to restrain the accused. Farhan was also placed under arrest by the police officers at the scene. Whilst Farhan was being placed under arrest, the accused continued to move around the scene and tried to interfere with Farhan’s arrest. He also told the arresting officers “eh, I bring him, I bring him. You all, you all low standard!”. As he was being placed under arrest by Sgt Irfan, the accused hurled vulgarities at SSgt Sumarni and stated “pukimak (which means “mother’s cunt” in Malay), if I get 302 also I don’t mind, you know!” which was a reference to being charged for s 302 of the Penal Code for murder. He also told SSgt Sumarni in the Malay language “you keep quiet, eh … go and tell your friends. Don’t step crazy with me. Wait I kill, stab your friend, die here”. The accused meant it as a warning to SSgt Sumarni to convey to her fellow police officers. SSgt Sumarni continually told him to calm down.

> 24.    At around 4.15 am at the service road of Block 755 Jurong West St 74, Singapore, the accused was being escorted by SSgt Sumarni and Sgt Irfan to the police vehicle. The accused was in handcuffs at that time. Despite that, the accused was uncooperative and intentionally threatened Sgt Irfan with death in Malay “Aku lepas kan benda ni, aku shoot kau sampai mati”, which meant “I let go of this thing, I shoot you till you die!” in English towards Sgt Irfan. The accused was threatening Sgt Irfan that if the handcuffs were released, he would beat Sgt Irfan to death. This caused Sgt Irfan to be alarmed and to fear for his safety, as Sgt Irfan had seen how the accused had attacked Sgt Chong earlier.

> 25.    By virtue of the foregoing, the accused has committed an offence under section 506 (2nd limb) of the Penal Code.

> **Facts relating to second charge DAC-904102-2020 (section 333 Penal Code)**

> 26.    At around 4.15 am at the service road of Block 755 Jurong West St 74, Singapore, as SSgt Sumarni and Sgt Irfan were escorting the accused to the police vehicle, Sgt Chen came over to provide assistance. During this time, the accused was in handcuffs and was being restrained by SSgt Sumarni and Sgt Irfan.

> 27.    When the accused saw Sgt Chen, he went straight to Sgt Chen and said “eh pukimak, fuck your mother cheebye”, which means “mother’s cunt, fuck your mother’s cunt” in English to Sgt Chen, a public servant in the discharge of his duties, before intentionally headbutting Sgt Chen’s face once with the intention to cause grievous hurt. The officers then told the accused to calm down. The accused replied in a mixture of English and Malay the words, “I love ah, I love ah, I love ah … hoo hoo! Haha, nothing lah!”. Sgt Chen began to bleed from the face as a result of the headbutt.

> 28.    Sgt Chen was conveyed by ambulance to Ng Teng Fong General Hospital. As a result of the accused’s headbutt, he sustained an undisplaced fracture of the nasal bone and 1cm laceration over the nasal bridge. He received 5 days of outpatient sick leave.

> 29.    By virtue of the foregoing, the accused has committed an offence under section 333 of the Penal Code.

> 30.    The accused’s actions in assaulting Sgt Chong and Sgt Chen, as well as criminally intimidating Sgt Irfan were captured by SSgt Sumarni’s body-worn camera.

> **Facts relating to third charge MAC-901862-2020 (section 3 Vandalism Act)**

> 31.    At around 4.30 am on 23 February 2020, the accused was placed in the rear passenger seat of a Police Fast Response Car (“FRC”) with the license plate of QX322T parked at the service road of Block 755 Jurong West St 74, Singapore.

> 32.    While in the car with the doors closed, accused begin head butting and kicking the right rear window and door of the FRC, causing damage to the door, which is public property belonging to the Singapore Police Force. The accused only stopped after his legs was restrained by the escorting Police Officers. The damage can be seen in the photograph below:

![](data:image;base64,)

> 33.    The FRC was taken out of service for repairs. By kicking the door of the FRC, the accused caused the right rear door to be misaligned. The repair costs incurred is SGD$1,255.48.

> 34.    By virtue of the foregoing, the accused has committed an offence under section 3 of the Vandalism Act (Cap 341, 2014 Rev Ed).

> 35.    Following his arrest, a blood sample was procured from the accused for blood alcohol analysis. A Health Sciences Authority (“HSA") report dated 3 March 2020 by Widodo Andreas, Analyst with the Analytical Toxicology Laboratory stated that on analysis of the accused’s blood sample, a result of 53mg of ethanol /100ml of blood was obtained.

> **Facts relating to DAC-920040-2020 (section 14(3) Societies Act)**

> 36.    Sometime in early 2007, whilst in secondary two, the accused was introduced to a gang member from the “Sio Kun Tong” Secret Society of the “18” group operating at Blk 131 Marsiling Rise. The accused was then invited to join the gang as a “fighter”. The accused thereafter joined the “Sio Kun Tong” Secret Society. Sometime in early 2008, the accused became acquainted with another member of the “Sio Kun Tong” Secret Society named “Beast” who had a gang operating at “Six Milestone”. The accused then switched gangs. In 2013, the accused was again acquainted with yet another member of the “Sio Kun Tong” Secret Society who had a gang operating at 131 Marsiling Rise. The accused then switched gangs to join that gang. Throughout his time as a member of the “Sio Kun Tong” Secret Society, he was informed by each gang that he could declare to others that he was from the “Sio Kun Tong” Secret Society if he encountered any trouble from rival gangs.

> 37.    On 21 March 2018, the accused was given a warning by the Secret Societies Branch of the Criminal Investigation Division for an offence under s 14(3) of the Societies Act for being a member of an unlawful society in relation to him being a “fighter” for the “Sio Kun Tong” Secret Society. The accused however continued to be a member of the “Sio Kun Tong” Secret Society. This included identifying himself as a “Sio Kun Tong” Secret Society member to SSgt Sumarni during his assault of the police officers on 23 February 2020.

> 38.    By virtue of the foregoing, from 22 March 2018 to 26 June 2020, in Singapore, the accused was a member of the ‘Sio Kun Tong’ Secret Society of the ‘18’ Group.

> 39.    The ‘Sio Kun Tong’ Secret Society is not a registered society in Singapore under the Societies Act (Cap 311, 2014 Rev Ed), and is thus an unlawful society.

> 40.    By virtue of the foregoing, the accused has committed an offence punishable under section 14(3) of the Societies Act.

> 41.    The accused stands charged accordingly.

## Antecedents

9       The accused had several antecedents as set out below. It would be relevant to note that in June 2012, he was placed on probation for using indecent, threatening, abusive or insulting words or behaviour towards a public servant under the Miscellaneous Offences (Public Order and Nuisance) Act, Cap 184 and in September 2017, he was sentenced to eight weeks’ imprisonment for using criminal force to deter a public servant in the discharge of his duty under s 353 of the PC.

## Areas of contention

13     As apparent from the table above, the parties were largely in agreement regarding the individual sentences. They also agreed that three of the sentences should be ordered to run consecutively. They disagreed on the following areas.

> (a)     Whether caning should be imposed for the common intention to cause grievous hurt charge.

> (b)     What should be the appropriate sentence for the criminal intimidation charge?

> (c)     Which of the three sentences should run consecutively, in particular, whether the sentences for the common intention to cause grievous hurt charge and the grievous hurt charge ought to be consecutive?

## Sentencing considerations

### Violence against police officers

14     Deterrence is the dominant sentencing consideration in cases involving violence against our police officers. As observed by the three-judge High Court coram in _Public Prosecutor v Yeo Ek Boon Jeffrey and another matter_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] 3 SLR 1080</span> (“_Jeffrey Yeo_”), police officers often find themselves in dangerous situations due to the nature of their work. Aside from being exposed to violence and aggression regularly, they frequently endanger their lives and risk their personal safety to maintain law and order to protect our society. The High Court in _Jeffrey Yeo_ noted poignantly that “surely those who preserve law and order and protect society dutifully deserve to feel assured that they will be protected adequately by the law that they uphold.”: at \[48\].

15     There is currently no established sentencing framework for the offence of voluntarily causing grievous hurt to a public servant under s 333 of the PC. _Jeffrey Yeo_ has however laid down a sentencing framework for the lesser offence of voluntarily causing hurt to public servants under s 332 of PC which is applicable to situations where hurt is caused to police officers and public servants who were performing duties akin to police duties at the material time: at \[52\]. The Prosecution submitted that while the maximum punishment under s 333 was significantly higher at 15 years’ imprisonment as compared to the maximum punishment of seven years’ imprisonment under s 332 of the PC and that any sentence for an offence under s 333 would have to take into account the higher maximum punishment under s 333, the framework in _Jeffrey Yeo_ nonetheless served as a useful guide. The Defence did not make any submission in this regard. I agreed with the Prosecution that _Jeffrey Yeo_ was a helpful reference because the underlying sentencing principles were equally applicable to s 333 of the PC.

16     I set out below the sentencing bands framework as formulated in _Jeffrey Yeo:_ at \[59\]_._ The sentencing bands are premised on offenders pleading guilty and not having relevant criminal antecedents: at \[61\]. _Jeffrey Yeo_ stated that an uplift may be justified where the offender has a bad criminal record: at \[61\].

<table align="left" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="Judg-2-tblr" frame="all" pgwide="1"><colgroup><col width="15.62%"><col width="49.92%"><col width="34.46%"></colgroup><tbody><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Category</b></p></td><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Circumstances</b></p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Sentencing band</b></p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1">1</p></td><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Lesser harm and lower culpability</p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Fine or up to one year’s imprisonment</p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1">2</p></td><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Greater harm and lower culpability</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">or</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Lesser harm and higher culpability</p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">One to three years’ imprisonment</p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="r" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1">3</p></td><td align="left" class="r" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Greater harm and higher culpability</p></td><td align="left" class="" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Three to seven years’ imprisonment.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>

  
  

### Common intention to cause grievous hurt charge – S 333 r/w 34 PC

17     As parties were aligned in their sentencing positions for the common intention to cause grievous hurt charge and differed only as to whether caning should be imposed, I shall briefly state the reasons why I agreed with their recommended sentence of between 33 to 36 months’ imprisonment and focus my grounds on why I decided to impose caning.

18     I accepted that an appropriate sentence for this charge would be between 33 to 36 months’ imprisonment for the following reasons:

> (a)     The police officers were responding to a report by a member of the public regarding a commotion at a HDB void deck in the wee hours of 4am. They had cause to be concerned and inquire further when they arrived at the scene and saw Farhan’s wife crying. The accused had however, intervened needlessly and aggressively in a situation that did not concern him.

> (b)     I agreed with the sentencing factors as submitted by the Prosecution[\[note: 5\]](#Ftn_5). To highlight a few of these factors, the accused had acted with contempt and malice towards the uniformed police officers. His attack on Sgt Chong was totally unprovoked and it was a sustained attack on Sgt Chong’s head and face, a vulnerable part of the body.

> (c)     In terms of parity of sentence, Farhan received 30 months’ imprisonment for this charge. The Prosecution argued that the accused should receive an imprisonment sentence of 36 months not only because his culpability was higher than Farhan’s, but he also had relevant antecedents and only entered his guilty plea some ten months later than Farhan[\[note: 6\]](#Ftn_6). While the Defence contended that the accused and Farhan shared similar culpability, it conceded that the accused should get a higher sentence than Farhan because the accused had a “related antecedent” in 2017 of using criminal force against a public servant under 353 PC whereas Farhan did not have related antecedents. I noted that the accused was the initiator of the assault on Sgt Chong. From \[13\] to \[17\] of the SOF, it was clear that the accused was the greater perpetrator against Sgt Chong. I therefore agreed with the Prosecution that his culpability was higher than Farhan’s. Coupled with the accused’s relevant antecedents, I agreed with parties that an uplift of between three to six months’ imprisonment from Farhan’s sentence would be fair.

> (d)     The Prosecution pointed out that if it had proceeded on a lower charge under s 332 of the PC, this case would have come within Category 3 of greater harm and higher culpability of the framework in _Jeffrey Yeo__[\[note: 7\]](#Ftn_7)._ It submitted that the accused would have been looking at a starting point of three years’ imprisonment which was within the Prosecution’s proposed sentencing range of 33 months to 36 months’ imprisonment and close to the 33 months’ imprisonment which the Defence had asked for. I agreed with the Prosecution that this would have been a Category 3 case thus it reinforced my view that the correct sentence for this charge was between 33 months to 36 months’ imprisonment.

#### Why caning was imposed

19     The High Court in _Jeffrey Yeo_ held that caning is appropriate as a general rule where an offender exhibits inordinate violence, uses weapons or attempts to snatch or to use the police officer’s firearms in the course of causing hurt to the police officer. The High Court held that other considerations justifying caning would be situations where the attack involved: a) a high degree of brutality or gratuitous violence, b) group or gang-related violence, c) resulted in very serious injuries to the police officer, d) occurred at a time and place where the public was put at risk and e) the offender’s antecedents demonstrated recalcitrance and a strong propensity to commit violent offences. The High Court stated that caning would generally be justified where the offence falls within Category 3 and in some cases, caning may be imposed within Category 2 where the circumstances and consequences of the attack are egregious and outrageous although the injury may not be severe: at \[74\].

20     As submitted by the Prosecution, the considerations for caning were present in this case[\[note: 8\]](#Ftn_8). The circumstances of the attack against Sgt Chong were egregious and outrageous which resulted in serious injuries to Sgt Chong. As evident from his antecedents, the accused had displayed escalating violent conduct towards law enforcement officers. Specific deterrence was necessary. I therefore ordered three strokes of the cane for this offence. In my view, notwithstanding that no caning was ordered for Farhan, it did not violate the parity principle because Farhan’s culpability was lower, and he did not have relevant antecedents.

21     The Defence cited two precedents which it argued were more aggravating than the present case, yet no caning was imposed. While the injuries in the precedents cited could be regarded as more serious, I found that the facts were distinguishable. For completeness, I shall deal with the precedents below.

22     The first precedent was _Public Prosecutor v GCA_ <span class="citation">\[2019\] SGDC 28</span> (“_GCA_”). In _GCA_, the offender pleaded guilty to numerous charges including an offence under section 333 of the PC. The offender who was diagnosed with Intermittent Explosive Disorder became agitated, aggressive, and violent during an interview with officers from the Ministry of Home Affairs. The officers had to restrain him and bring him to the floor. When he was on the floor, he tried to kick the officers who were near him and in the process, he kicked the victim on the right hand when the victim was trying to restrain the offender’s legs. The victim sustained a tissue injury of his right thumb, but he continued to suffer beyond his 21 days of medical leave. His daily functioning and quality of life was affected significantly, and the doctor informed him that he might lose the flexibility of his right thumb and he might not completely recover from his injury. The offender’s psychiatric condition had contributed to the commission of his offences. He did not have any prior antecedents. The District Judge sentenced the offender to 30 months’ imprisonment for the s 333 offence. On appeal, the sentence was reduced to 24 months’ imprisonment.

23     The second precedent cited by the Defence was _Public Prosecutor v Lee Cheng Yan_ <span class="citation">\[2020\] SGDC 216</span> (“_Lee Cheng Yan_”). The offender in _Lee Cheng Yan_ was convicted after trial of one count of voluntarily causing grievous hurt to the victim, a traffic police officer under s 333 of the PC, amongst other offences. The victim had signaled to the offender to stop his car and when he was near the driver’s door which had its window down, the offender suddenly reversed his car, swerved to the right, and accelerated forward. The victim’s elbow guard was caught by the car, but when he shouted at the offender to stop, the offender continued to drive on as he was trying to evade arrest and dragged the victim along for about 124m before the victim fell off the car and onto the road. The victim was given 21 days of hospitalisation leave. He continued to feel pain on his lower back when he carried heavy loads and could no longer perform all his police duties and was downgraded. The trial judge noted that the offender had not shown remorse by mounting an unmeritorious defence despite the overwhelming evidence against him and sentenced the offender to four years’ imprisonment for this offence. The sentence was upheld on appeal.

24     In both precedents above, while the offenders’ actions were wholly unjustified, I observed that there was some triggering event. In _GCA_, the offender committed the offence when he was resisting the restraining efforts of the officers and his psychiatric condition had a contributory link. In _Lee Cheng Yan_, the offender was trying to flee from the scene when he committed the offence. In the present case, the accused was the troublemaker, and his attack was totally gratuitous. In _GCA_, the offender was simply kicking out at anyone near him. In _Lee Cheng Yan_, the offender callously disregarded the dangerous situation the victim was in. In the present case, the accused intentionally punched Sgt Chong’s face, which was a vulnerable part of the body. In _GCA_, the offender had no prior antecedents while the offender in _Lee Cheng Yan_ only had traffic related antecedents. In the present case, the accused had relevant antecedents. Specific deterrence was therefore of greater prominence in this case.

25     For the reasons given above, I decided that it would be right to impose caning of three strokes on the accused.

### Grievous hurt charge – S 333 PC

26     As tabulated at \[12\] above, the parties were in close agreement on the sentence for this charge. The Prosecution submitted that a sentence of 21 months’ imprisonment was warranted but that it should be calibrated downwards to 18 months’ imprisonment on the totality principle. The Defence submitted for a sentence of 18 months’ imprisonment. I accepted that the appropriate sentencing range was between 18 months to 21 months’ imprisonment for the reasons set out below.

> (a)     I agreed with the sentencing factors submitted by the Prosecution[\[note: 9\]](#Ftn_9). Sgt Chen had arrived at the scene as part of the additional resources. By then the accused had been handcuffed and was being escorted to the police vehicle but he was undeterred and launched an unprovoked attack on Sgt Chen by headbutting Sgt Chen’s face. The accused then sadistically uttered “I love ah, I love ah, I love ah”[^10]. His actions were clearly borne out of malice.

> (b)     The sentencing range of 18 months to 21 months’ imprisonment was in line with the precedent in _GCA_ where on appeal, the offender’s sentence was reduced from 30 months to 24 months’ imprisonment. The victim in _GCA_ suffered more serious injuries than Sgt Chen. Hence, the sentence in this case should be lower than 24 months’ imprisonment.

> (c)     With reference to the sentencing framework in _Jeffrey Yeo_, I agreed with the Prosecution that if it had been a lesser charge under s 332 of the PC, it would fall under Category 2 within the sentencing band of one to three years’ imprisonment. A sentence of between 18 to 21 months’ imprisonment was well within the band and could not be said to be excessive.

### Criminal intimidation charge – S 506 PC

27     The criminal intimidation charge pertained to a threat to cause death hence the offence was punishable under the second limb of s 506 of the PC. The sentence for this charge was a point of contention between the parties. The Prosecution argued that the appropriate sentence should be 15 months’ imprisonment and adjusted to 12 months’ imprisonment on the totality principle while the Defence submitted that the appropriate sentence was six months’ imprisonment.

28     The High Court in _Ong Ting Ting v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2004\] 4 SLR(R) 53</span> (“_Ong Ting Ting_”) held that the usual tariff for a charge under this limb was a term of six months: at \[51\]. In _Tan Kay Beng v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2006\] 4 SLR(R) 10</span> (“_Tan Kay Beng_”), the High Court noted that it was published in the _Sentencing Practice in the Subordinate Courts_ (LexisNexis, 2nd Ed, 2003) at p 217 that where the threat to kill was without a weapon, the sentencing range for offenders with no prior record was between six to 12 months’ imprisonment: at \[45\]. In _Public Prosecutor v Luan Yuanxin_ \[2002\] 1 SLR (R) 613, the High Court held that a threat to cause death made in all seriousness by someone who was not incapable of carrying out the threat was something that should never be taken lightly particularly so when a weapon was used as part of the threat: at \[9\]. It further stated that if the victim was not only alarmed by the threat but had feared for his safety, it was an aggravating factor that went towards the seriousness of the offence: at \[10\]. The High Court in _Tan Kay Beng_ however cautioned that while it was correct that aggravated criminal intimidation would attract higher punishment, the sentence meted out must be tempered by both proportionality and the specific factual matrix, and that sentencing guidelines should not be religiously applied nor adhered to mechanically: at \[45\].

29     In the present case, I agreed with the Prosecution[\[note: 11\]](#Ftn_11) and the Defence[^12] that it was aggravating that it was a police officer that the accused was threatening to kill. Sgt Irfan was not only alarmed by the threat, but he had also feared for his safety because he had just witnessed the accused attacking Sgt Chong in the common intention to cause grievous hurt charge[^13]. The Prosecution pointed out that around that time, the accused was telling SSgt Sumarni repeatedly within the earshot of Sgt Irfan that he would kill and stab the police officers to death[^14]. That said, when the accused committed the criminal intimidation charge against Sgt Irfan, he had by then been handcuffed and there were five other police officers present. While I noted that the accused subsequently targeted and headbutted Sgt Chen despite being handcuffed, no weapons were involved throughout. I had also considered the two TIC charges where the accused had verbally abused two separate police officers namely SSgt Surmani and Sgt Chen. On the facts, I was of the view that a sentence of six months’ imprisonment as recommended by the Defence would be adequate for this charge. In any event, I ordered this sentence to run concurrently.

30     The sentence I imposed was in line with the sentencing tariff and sentencing range as laid down by the High Court. It was also an appropriate sentence having regard to the precedents cited. I highlight two such precedents below.

31     The first precedent was _Gan Sim Lim v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2005\] 3 SLR(R) 358</span> (“_Gan Sim Lim_”) where I agreed with the Defence that the facts there were more serious than the present facts. In _Gan Sim Lim_, the offender had entered his ex-girlfriend’s apartment without permission, broken into her bedroom and then proceeded to punch, slap, and kick her. He also pointed a pair of scissors at her and threatened to kill her. The victim was placed under so much fear that she was willing to comply with any of his demands. The offender had claimed trial. He had no recorded history of violence. His sentence of six months’ imprisonment for the criminal intimidation charge under the second limb was affirmed on appeal.

32     The second precedent was _Public Prosecutor v Jonathan James Hudson_ <span class="citation">\[2020\] SGDC 256</span> (“_Hudson_”). The offender who was untraced, had pleaded guilty to multiple offences including one of criminal intimidation by threatening to cause death to a police officer by uttering “Sir, I make sure I murder you”. The District Judge held that an imprisonment term of four months was appropriate because the threat consisted of only words with no weapons and uttered once although it was against a police officer who was on duty: \[38\]. The offender subsequently withdrew his appeal. Since the facts in the present case were more aggravated, I agreed with the Defence that there should be an uplift of two months’ imprisonment.

### Vandalism charge – S 3 VA

33     I agreed with both the Prosecution and the Defence that the appropriate sentence would be five months’ imprisonment and three strokes of the cane. This was a serious offence where the law provided for mandatory caning. The accused not only headbutted the car window and door, but he also kicked them and caused damage amounting to $1255.48 for which there was no restitution. He only stopped his rampage after his legs were restrained by the escorting police officers[\[note: 15\]](#Ftn_15). A sentence of five months’ imprisonment and the minimum three strokes of the cane would be fair in the present case. I had ordered this sentence to run concurrently.

### Member of unlawful society charge – S 14(3) of the SA

34     The Prosecution submitted for the “usual tariff” of three months’ imprisonment[\[note: 16\]](#Ftn_16). The Defence did not make any alternative submission[^17]. For this offence, the police warned the accused on 21 March 2018 against his illegal involvement as a “fighter” in “Sio Kun Tong”[^18]. The accused ignored the warning and continued to be a member of the secret society for more than two years from 22 March 2018 until 26 June 2020 which was not a short duration. On the facts, I was satisfied that a sentence of three months’ imprisonment would be appropriate.

## The three sentences to run consecutively

35     S 307(1) of the Criminal Procedure Code, Cap 224 (“CPC”) stipulates that where a person is sentenced to imprisonment for at least three distinct offences, the court must order the sentences for at least two of those offences to run consecutively. As a general rule, sentences for unrelated offences should also run consecutively while sentences for offences that form part of a single transaction should run concurrently, subject to the requirement in s 307(1) of the CPC: _PP v Raveen Balakrishnan_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] 5 SLR 799</span> (“_Raveen_”) at \[98(b)\].

36     As I have mentioned at the outset, although the parties agreed that three of the imprisonment terms should run consecutively, they disagreed on which of the sentences ought to be so ordered. The Prosecution argued that both s 333 PC charges and the vandalism charge should run consecutively. To ensure that the totality principle was not infringed, it submitted that the individual sentences could be adjusted downwards to yield a total sentence of between 54 to 60 months’ imprisonment and six strokes of the cane with caning to be imposed on the common intention to cause grievous hurt charge. On the other hand, the Defence submitted that only one of the s 333 charges should run consecutively which would be the common intention to cause grievous hurt charge together with the vandalism charge and the criminal intimidation charge to make a total sentence of 44 months’ imprisonment and three strokes of the cane with no caning to be imposed for the common intention to cause grievous hurt charge.

37     I agreed with the parties that it would be fair to order three out of the five proceeded charges to run consecutively to reflect the culpability of the accused. As regards whether one or both s 333 PC offences were to run consecutively, I accepted the submissions of the Prosecution that the two offences were distinct and did not form part of the same criminal transaction[\[note: 19\]](#Ftn_19). The police officers managed to subdue the accused after his attack on Sgt Chong. The accused had been restrained and handcuffed for at least four minutes when he launched his attack on Sgt Chen. Aside from the time interval between the two offences, both attacks occurred at different locations, one at the void deck in furtherance of the common intention with Farhan and the other at the service road involving a different victim who had arrived as additional police resources. There was thus no proximity in time, space and continuity between the two charges. In this regard, the Defence conceded that there was some time lapse between the two offences and made no submission on whether they formed part of the same transaction[^20].

38     I further agreed with the Prosecution that adopting the recommendations of the Defence to order both s 333 PC offences to run concurrently would essentially mean that the accused would only receive 33 months’ imprisonment for beating up and causing grievous hurt to two police officers at two separate points in time. It would be pertinent to note that Farhan who was sentenced to 30 months’ imprisonment for his corresponding common intention to cause grievous hurt charge also faced a lesser s 332 PC charge for causing hurt to Sgt Irfan for which he was sentenced to 12 weeks’ imprisonment. Farhan’s sentences were ordered to run concurrently. Farhan committed both these offences at the void deck at around the same time hence they were part of the same transaction. This was not the situation for the accused where his s 333 PC offences were distinct transactions. It would be disproportionate to the accused’s overall culpability and criminality to order both his s 333 PC offences to run concurrently.[\[note: 21\]](#Ftn_21)

39     I therefore ordered the sentences for both the common intention to cause grievous hurt charge and the grievous hurt charge to run consecutively. In view of this, I imposed the sentence at the lower end of the sentencing range. Hence, I imposed a sentence of 33 months’ imprisonment for the common intention to cause grievous hurt charge and a sentence of 18 months’ imprisonment for the grievous hurt charge.

40     In addition, I ordered the sentence of three months’ imprisonment for the member of unlawful society charge to run consecutively. This offence was totally unrelated to the other proceeded charges and represented a different legally protected interest.

41     I should state that in adjusting the sentences in this case, I had considered the accused’s mitigation plea and taken into account his plea of guilt. Although there was overwhelming evidence against him and the Prosecution would have no difficulty proving the charges, I accorded some weight to his guilty plea as it had saved the court time and resources.

42     As set out below, the accused’s aggregate sentence is therefore 54 months imprisonment (four and a half years’ imprisonment) and six strokes of the cane. In my view, the global sentence was sufficient and proportionate to the accused’s overall criminality: _Raveen_ at \[98(c)\].

## Backdating of sentence

43     I backdated the sentence for the accused to 23 February 2020 which was the date the accused was arrested, to take into account his periods of remand and to exclude the periods where he was on bail. He was on bail from 25 February 2020 to 7 April 2022.

44     The accused is currently serving his sentence.

1st CHARGE (AMENDED)

> You, are charged that you, on the 23th February 2020, at or about 4:08 am, at the void deck of Block 755 Jurong West Street 74, Singapore, together with one Muhammad Farhan Jaffri and in furtherance of the common intention of you both, did voluntarily cause grievous hurt to a public servant, Sergeant Chong Jia Wei, a Police Officer with the Singapore Police Force, in the discharge of his duty as such public servant, to wit, by punching and kicking him multiple times on his face and body, thereby causing him to be, during the space of 29 days, unable to follow his ordinary pursuits, and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 333 read with Section 34 of the Penal Code, Chapter 224.

2nd CHARGE

> You, are charged that you, on the 23th February 2020, at or about 4:15 am, at the service road of Block 755 Jurong West Street 74, Singapore, did voluntarily cause grievous hurt to a public servant, Sergeant Chen Jian Da, a Police Officer with the Singapore Police Force, in the discharge of his duty as such public servant, to wit, by headbutting him on the nose and causing a nasal laceration and nasal fracture, and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 333 of the Penal Code, Chapter 224.

> (c)    DAC-919124-2020 (exhibit C3A)

5th Charge

> You, are charged that you, on the 23th February 2020, at or about 4:15am, at the service road of Block 755 Jurong West Street 74, Singapore, did with the intent to cause alarm to one victim namely Muhammad Irfan Bin Misran, threaten the said victim with death (2nd limb), to wit, by uttering the Malay words “Aku lepas kan benda ni, aku shoot kau sampai mati!” which means “I let go of this thing, I _shoot_ you until die” in English directed at the victim, and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 506 (2nd limb) of the Penal Code, Chapter 224.

7th CHARGE

> You, are charged that you, from 22 March 2018 to 26 June 2020, in Singapore are a member of an unlawful society, to wit the ‘Sio Kun Tong’ Secret Society of the ‘18’ Group and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 14(3) of the Societies Act, Chapter 311 (2014 Rev Ed).

3rd CHARGE

> You, are charged that you, on the 23th February 2020, at or about 4:40am, while at the rear passenger seat of a Police Fast Response Car bearing registration number QX322T (“FRC”) at the service road of Block 755 Jurong West St 74, Singapore, did commit an act of vandalism, to wit, by kicking the rear right passenger door of the FRC, which is a public property belonging to the Singapore Police Force, causing damage to the door which was misaligned which cost $1,255.48 to repair, and you have hereby committed an offence under Section 3 of the Vandalism Act, Chapter 341.
